definition.value: Legislation related to the legal rights afforded to victims of crime.
Bills designed to promote human rights on social, regional, and domestic levels.
Bills which refer to the rights of a group or collective of persons.
Bills related to LGBTQIA+ rights.
Bills related to transgender rights.

The common name for a law that defines access to public toilets by gender (restrooms)—or for transgender individuals. Bathroom bills affect access to sex-segregated public facilities for an individual based on a determination of their sex as defined in some specific way—such as their sex as assigned at birth, their sex as listed on their birth certificate, or the sex that corresponds to their gender identity.
Violent acts committed against intersex people.
Acts of violence committed against gay men.
Various forms of negativity towards gay men as individuals, as couples, or as a social group.
Discrimination against Two-Spirit people.
A person who identifies as xenogender.
A bisexual person who is an author.
A gay person who is an author.
A bisexual person who is Native American.
A North American Indigenous person who is bisexual.
A queer Black person who identifies as Blaqueer or BlaQ.
Care between individuals of similar circumstance, oftentimes used in reference to care of individuals with HIV.
Any of various forms of care related to sexuality.
Rights affecting gay people.
Legal rights and freedoms relating to sexuality and sexual health that vary amongst countries around the world.
Celibacy as observed among clergy in certain religious traditions.
Fear of, dislike of or prejudice against hijra.
A pejorative which implies a person who is hijra or is directed primarily at hijra.

A gay man who is not out, or has not made their identity known, to others. A person may be closeted to family but not close friends or they may be closeted to everyone, depending on the circumstances.

A bisexual person who is not out, or has not made their identity known, to others. A person may be closeted to family but not close friends or they may be closeted to everyone, depending on the circumstances.

A transgender person who is not out, or has not made their identity known, to others. A person may be closeted to family but not close friends or they may be closeted to everyone, depending on the circumstances.
A sexual relationship involving three people.
A sexual relationship involving two people.
A romantic relationship involving three people.
Sexual intercourse occurring between three individuals.
Sexual intercourse occurring between four individuals.
A relationship which is strictly monogamous.
A relationship which is polygamous.
A relationship which is not monogamous.
A polygamous relationship between three people.
A relationship between two or more persons or groups which is competitive in nature.
A competitive relationship which is romantic in nature.
A competitive romantic relationship involving three people.
A polygamous relationship between four people.
A polygamous relationship between five people.
A polygamous relationship between six people.
A polygamous relationship in which all three people are in relationship with one another.
A polygamous relationship in which one person is in a relationship with two others, who are not necessarily in relationship with one another.

A non-monogamous relationship in partners (by agreement) are allowed o have multiple romantic and/or sexual relationships as long as they do not discuss it with their primary partner or let it interfere with their primary partner’s daily life.

A relationship structure in which a partnered person is permitted to have additional relationships on the condition that their partner does not meet the other people involved or know anything about those additional relationships.
A person who uses two sets of pronouns, such as a person who uses she/her and they/them pronouns.
A lesbian who uses she/they pronouns.
A person who uses two sets of pronouns, such as a person who uses he/him pronouns.
A person who uses the pronouns she, they, her, and them in English as their third-person pronouns.
